// Section 5: Execution, Complexity, and Creativity

= Execution, Complexity, and Creativity

== Project Goals

The following goals were established for this project:

+ Forge and heat-treat a set of push engraving gravers from tool steel,
  replicating the period practice of engravers making their own tools.
+ Turn period-accurate mushroom handles from dense hardwood.
+ Prepare a copper plate using period-appropriate methods.
+ Convert Moretto da Brescia's c. 1540–41 _Conversion of Saint Paul_
  (Santa Maria presso San Celso, Milan) @moretto-conversion into a reversed
  line drawing suitable for engraving, exercising personal artistic
  interpretation in the translation from painted tonal values to line work.
+ Transfer the design and engrave the plate using push engraving only,
  employing the full period line vocabulary (line, hatching, cross-hatching,
  stippling).
+ Produce a finished engraved plate that functions both as a decorative
  object and as a printing plate capable of producing paper impressions.
+ Document every material, tool, and technique decision with reference to
  period sources.

== Personal Interpretation

This project is not a direct copy of an existing engraving. The source
material is a painting, and the conversion of a painted image into engraved
line work requires substantial personal artistic interpretation. The engraver
must decide: which painted values become lines and which become negative
space; how to represent color and tonal gradation using only black-and-white
line vocabulary; how to simplify or adapt the composition for the constraints
of the burin; and how to manage the reversal of the image. This process of
converting paintings to engravings was itself a recognized and respected
skill in the period — Marcantonio Raimondi was celebrated specifically for
his ability to translate Raphael's paintings into copper plate engravings,
a workshop practice documented in detail in Lisa Pon's _Raphael, Dürer, and
Marcantonio Raimondi_ @pon-raphael-marcantonio.

== Challenges and Solutions

=== Challenge 1: Learning Push Engraving as a New Skill

Push engraving requires a fundamentally different hand motion from the
engraver's prior experience with chasing and repoussé (hammer-driven) and
woodblock carving (knife-driven). The burin is pushed with palm pressure,
requiring development of new muscle memory for control of line depth, width,
and curvature. _Solution:_ extensive practice on scrap copper with straight
lines, curves, and basic scroll elements before beginning the finished
plate, following the progression recommended by experienced engravers
@engraverscafe-practice.

=== Challenge 2: Converting Painted Tonal Values to Line Work

A painting has continuous tonal gradation; an engraving has only lines.
Every area of the composition must be interpreted as some combination of
line density, and there is no way to correct major compositional decisions
once cutting has begun. _Solution:_ extensive preparatory drawing in pencil,
working through the tonal interpretation on paper before committing to the
plate. Multiple studies at different simplification levels to determine the
appropriate level of detail for the engraver's current skill.

=== Challenge 3: Image Reversal

The engraved image must be cut in reverse so that it prints correctly. This
requires the engraver to work with a mirrored version of the design, which
can be disorienting. _Solution:_ prepare the reversed drawing carefully
before transfer, and work from the transferred lines on the plate rather
than from memory or a non-reversed reference.

=== Challenge 4: Sharpening to Precise Geometry

A burin that is not perfectly sharpened with correct face and heel geometry
will dig in, skip, or produce ragged lines. Maintaining consistent geometry
during resharpening (which is required frequently) is critical. _Solution:_
develop a consistent sharpening routine using the natural stone and strop,
with the thumbnail test to verify sharpness before each session. Practice
resharpening until it becomes reliable and fast.

=== Challenge 5: Tool Making with Precision Geometry

While the engraver has prior experience making chasing tools, gravers
require more precise geometry at the cutting face. The face angle, heel
angle, and point geometry must all be correct for the tool to function
properly. _Solution:_ forge multiple blanks and practice grinding geometry
on the waterstones before committing to the final tool set.

== Future Avenues of Exploration

This project opens several avenues for further development:

/ Niello fill: Adding niello (a sulfur-silver-copper-lead compound) to the
  engraved lines to create a high-contrast decorative object in the
  Florentine goldsmith tradition. This would add a new skill (niello
  preparation and application) and connect the project to the Italian
  engraving tradition of Finiguerra and his contemporaries. The standard
  scholarly catalogue of early Italian engraving — Levenson, Oberhuber,
  and Sheehan's _Early Italian Engravings from the National Gallery of Art_
  — treats the Florentine niello-print tradition in detail
  @levenson-early-italian-engravings, and Cellini's _Trattati_ covers
  sixteenth-century goldsmiths' niello practice firsthand from a working
  Florentine shop @cellini-treatises.

/ Intaglio printing: Building or obtaining a simple screw press and pulling
  editions of paper prints from the plate. Period presses were simple wooden
  constructions, and a period-accurate press is itself a viable reenactment
  project.

/ Engraving directly on liturgical or decorative objects: Moving from flat
  plates to three-dimensional objects such as chalice bands, paxes, or belt
  fittings, replicating the goldsmith's decorative practice that predated
  printmaking.

/ Sulfur casting: Making sulfur casts from the engraved plate to record the
  design, replicating the documented practice of Finiguerra and other
  Renaissance goldsmiths as recorded by Vasari @vasari-bondanella and
  reassessed in A. Hyatt Mayor's _Prints and People_ @mayor-prints-people.

/ More complex compositions: Progressing to multi-figure scenes with full
  cross-hatched shading in the manner of Dürer's master engravings.

/ Period pigment preparation: Making printing ink from lampblack ground in
  linseed oil, and preparing laid paper, to produce fully period-accurate
  prints.
